{
  "answer": "**Parāśara Smṛti** frames itself as \"a compendium of *dharmaśāstra*, consisting of five hundred and ninety-two verses.\"[^1]\n\n**Vīramitrodaya** frames itself as a compilation drawing from earlier sages such as Hārīta, Gobhila, Parāśara, Nārada, and others.[^2]\n\nNo other works in the corpus explicitly frame themselves as a digest, compendium, or summary of earlier authorities. Many Indic *smṛti* texts (e.g., Manusmṛti, Yājñavalkya Smṛti) cite authorities but do not self-describe as such.\n\n[^1]: Parāśara Smṛti, [Chapter 12, paragraph p-de6d1a](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/12/translation/#p-de6d1a).\n\n[^2]: Vīramitrodaya, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-19342f](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-19342f).",
